  summary: "Distributed responsibility theory addresses situations where multiple agents contribute to an outcome, making it difficult to assign blame or credit solely to one individual. It explores how responsibility can be shared across a group or system, even when no single agent is fully in control. In AI policy, this theory is crucial for understanding accountability when AI systems cause harm, as AI development and deployment often involve many actors (developers, users, regulators). It helps in designing legal and ethical frameworks for AI governance.",
